---
title: 'The Quiet Face of Greed'
date: '2026-03-05'
category: 'essay'
excerpt: 'Greed does not always look like hunger. Sometimes it looks like fear.'
---

We have been taught to recognize greed in its loudest form — the billionaire hoarding, the politician stealing, the hand that takes more than it needs from a shared table.

But I am more interested in its quieter face.

The greed that lives in ordinary people. The kind that whispers rather than shouts. The friend who can't celebrate your win without measuring it against their own. The person who holds information like currency, releasing it only when it benefits them. The one who says *I love you* but means *stay where I can see you.*

Greed in its quiet form is not about money. It is about control. About the deep animal fear that there is not enough — not enough love, not enough recognition, not enough time — and that someone else having more means you will have less.

The antidote is not generosity alone. It is the belief, practiced daily, that abundance is possible. That their win is not your loss. That the table can always be extended.

Greed shrinks in the presence of that belief. Not immediately. But eventually.
